The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT45 NT81  
   NT81 has no further non-terminal expansions; it can only produce one of the terminals t71, t30, or t3.  
   Therefore, any string derived via this rule must end with t71, t30, or t3.  
   The given string ends with t28, so it cannot be derived through this branch.

2. S → NT19 NT67  
   NT67 also has no further non-terminal expansions; it always produces the fixed two-terminal sequence t82 t5.  
   Hence any string derived via this rule must end with … t82 t5.  
   The given string ends with … t30 t28, so it cannot be derived through this branch either.

Since these are the only two ways to expand S and neither can yield a string whose last symbols match the required t30 t28 ending, the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT45 NT81  
   • NT81 can generate only a single terminal: t71, t30, or t3.  
   • Therefore the entire string would have to end with one of these three tokens.  
   • The given string ends with t49, so this production cannot yield the string.

2. S → NT19 NT67  
   • NT67 → NT30 NT2, and NT30 → t82 while NT2 → t5, so NT67 generates exactly the pair “t82 t5”.  
   • The substring “t82 t5” never appears in the given string (t82 does not appear at all), so this production cannot yield the string either.

Since neither of the only two possible top-level derivations can produce the provided token sequence, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT45 NT81  
   – NT81 is always a single terminal: 't71', 't30', or 't3'.  
   – Therefore any string derived with this rule must end with one of those three tokens.  
   – The given string ends with t39, so this derivation cannot match it.

2. S → NT19 NT67  
   – NT67 → NT30 NT2 → 't82' 't5'.  
   – Hence any string derived along this branch must contain the token t5 (and in fact end with … t82 t5).  
   – The token t5 does not appear anywhere in the given string.

Since the only two possible top-level derivations are both incompatible with the required terminal sequence, the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

The start symbol S can expand in exactly two ways:

1. S → NT45 NT81  
   Here NT81 produces a single terminal (t71, t30 or t3).  
   Therefore the last symbol of any string derived through this rule must be one of {t71, t30, t3}.  
   The given string ends with t26, so this expansion cannot generate it.

2. S → NT19 NT67  
   NT67 is fixed: NT67 → NT30 NT2 → t82 t5.  
   Thus any string derived through this rule must end with the two-symbol suffix t82 t5.  
   The given string ends with t77 t26, so this expansion also cannot generate it.

Since neither possible expansion of the start symbol can match the ending of the provided string, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

   NT81 is a single–terminal non-terminal, expanding only to t71, t30 or t3.  
   Hence any string derived via this rule must end with t71, t30 or t3.  
   The given string ends with t5, so this alternative cannot generate it.

2. S → NT19 NT67  
   NT67 is fixed: NT67 → NT30 NT2 → t82 t5.  
   Therefore a string derived through this rule must finish with “… t82 t5”.  
   The given string indeed ends with t82 t5, so we need the prefix of length 39
   to be generated by NT19.

   NT19, however, has only  
   NT19 → NT84 NT8 → t77 t83 (starts with t77) or  
   NT19 → NT60 NT5 → t84 … (starts with t84).  
   The 39-token prefix of the string begins with t82, not t77 or t84, hence
   NT19 cannot generate it.

Since neither of the two possible derivations from S matches the string, the grammar does not generate the given string.
